of experiments over the last decade. All of those experiments, a lot of them are medical,

00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:12.160
a lot of them are high radiation, but there's a lot of other things that go out there.

00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:19.160
All of those have generated some type of patent, potentially, products that benefit back to

00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:28.160
the economy as well as humankind. So they all, and you see the commercial Velcro,

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:32.160
memory foam, all of those things, some of the things that are out there right now were all created

00:21:32.160 --> 00:21:39.160
because NASA was looking at ways of doing things. But we have a software transition site

00:21:39.160 --> 00:21:42.160
to where you can see what kind of software we've open sourced out there, and you can utilize

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:48.160
that software for free for, I'm trying to remember, for like three years.

00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:51.160
And then you've got to make some kind of decision how you want to commercialize that.

00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:56.160
We've got a lot of different technology transfer groups where a lot of our technology

00:21:56.160 --> 00:21:59.160
that's being created, we eventually try to get that out into the public.

00:21:59.160 --> 00:22:04.160
We want the economy to utilize our things that are being created.

00:22:04.160 --> 00:22:09.160
And there's several companies that have been created based on technology that started at NASA,

00:22:09.160 --> 00:22:17.160
gone out into the public, and it has provided thousands of jobs and more money back into the economy.

00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:21.160
That's fascinating. Thanks, David. I just put a link into the chat.

00:22:21.160 --> 00:22:32.160
