00:22:32.160 --> 00:22:36.160
That's one of them, but no, let me, I'll look for him while we're talking.

00:22:36.160 --> 00:22:42.160
Okay. Or you can share it later, too. I try and guess at some of the links as we go.

00:22:42.160 --> 00:22:47.160
I see Sam just asked a question. You put the little star, so I'll read it.

00:22:47.160 --> 00:22:55.160
Is People Analytics at NASA using R or RStudio products? And if so, what impact has this had?

00:22:55.160 --> 00:23:03.160
So, yes, the simple answer is yes. We are using RStudio ecosystem.

00:23:03.160 --> 00:23:09.160
We've got the RStudio Connect, the Workbench, and Package Manager. We're licensed for that.

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:18.160
And it's having a lot of impact as far, at least in my opinion anyway, for how our capabilities of what we're trying to do.

00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:26.160
When I joined the People Analytics team, you know, again, a couple of years ago, it was primarily a,

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:31.160
the team primarily walked around with their laptops. I hate to say this, with their laptops with Tableau on it and said,

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:35.160
okay, here's what I did. Here's the visualization and I'll share it with you.

00:23:35.160 --> 00:23:40.160
So the, you know, I had to work on making these things readily available or easily accessible,

00:23:40.160 --> 00:23:43.160
not only to our, to the team, but to the end users.

00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:51.160
So RStudio was one of those ways of doing that, to be able to create visualizations and reports and presentations

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:57.160
and everything else you can do within the R ecosystem and make that easily accessible to not only the,

00:23:57.160 --> 00:24:01.160
the data scientists and the team, but to the end users to see those visualizations.

00:24:01.160 --> 00:24:07.160
But at the same time, we were working across NASA to create what we call the Enterprise Data Platform,

00:24:07.160 --> 00:24:12.160
which was trying to develop that, that pipeline on those workflows to,

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:17.160
to make it easy to transmit that data from our authoritative source to a presentation layer.

00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:26.160
The OCIO team was working on developing a Tableau server instance with an Alteryx no-code, low-code capability.

00:24:26.160 --> 00:24:30.160
And then connecting that to, to the authoritative data source.

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:35.160
That was their start of a Enterprise Data Platform.

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:43.160
Now, it's, that's okay in my mind for those that are more of a data analyst.

00:24:43.160 --> 00:24:49.160
And those that are more focused on creating visualizations and creating,

00:24:49.160 --> 00:24:55.160
using data that's already been curated to create those reports and those visualizations.

00:24:55.160 --> 00:25:00.160
For a data scientist or data engineer who's actually trying to use data that's dirty, you know,

00:25:00.160 --> 00:25:05.160
and try to clean it up and make it more tidy, we needed other tools to do that.

00:25:05.160 --> 00:25:08.160
And that's where, you know, utilizing RStudio.

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:15.160
And one of the reasons I chose, went with RStudio is because of their continuous growth

00:25:15.160 --> 00:25:20.160
in how they're using multiple languages, especially Python and R combination of those two.

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:25.160
Because half my team was Python and half my team was R.

00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:28.160
I needed to figure out a way that they could both utilize those things.

00:25:28.160 --> 00:25:34.160
So we kind of used a combination of RStudio and also VS Code, you know, for some things.

00:25:34.160 --> 00:25:38.160
But we're able to still create good applications, both in R and Python,

00:25:38.160 --> 00:25:45.160
and put those on the Connect server, which has provided a lot of value internally within our organization

00:25:45.160 --> 00:25:52.160
and starting to show some value externally as they're seeing what we're developing and how we're migrating to that.

00:25:52.160 --> 00:25:54.160
I wish we were a little further along.

00:25:54.160 --> 00:26:01.160
We just, again, I don't have enough people, enough staff to get these things to the level I would like.

00:26:01.160 --> 00:26:07.160
Such much that I'm probably, well, I'm the admin for the R servers right now,

00:26:07.160 --> 00:26:12.160
only because I'm the one that has the most experience on administrating those.

00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:20.160
And I need to get the OCIO group to understand, OK, now you guys have to take this over and get people trained up on it.

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:23.160
So probably a lot more information than you wanted.

00:26:23.160 --> 00:26:25.160
That's great, David. Thank you.

