Thanks for all the great questions here, too.

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:03.160
Maybe shifting gears a little bit, somebody asked,

00:28:03.160 --> 00:28:13.160
what's important when it comes to leadership and people management in such a technical company with numbers-driven projects?

00:28:13.160 --> 00:28:15.160
Listening and communication.

00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:21.160
It's probably, from a leadership standpoint, really understanding the needs,

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:28.160
not only of your end users, your customers, or who you're delivering your products to,

00:28:28.160 --> 00:28:35.160
but also understanding the needs and constraints that your team may be having.

00:28:35.160 --> 00:28:45.160
It's one thing just to go out and do this, but you really have to be there for them to break some of the roadblocks they may be having,

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:47.160
but also just provide a lending ear sometimes.

00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:55.160
I've got a lot of early career people that have come in here, and you need to be their mentor.

00:28:55.160 --> 00:29:01.160
You need to be sometimes just a coach or a friend or just a listening ear just to get that understanding.

00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:08.160
I had a conversation with one of my team members this morning, just as a code review.

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:11.160
He was having, and Rachel, I may get back with you on this,

00:29:11.160 --> 00:29:17.160
we're having an issue with the Dash app on the Connect server that it works well on the desktop,

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:24.160
but when we post it on the Connect server, the callbacks run very, very slow.

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:30.160
So we were just doing some code review, and he just really appreciated the time with just me sitting down with him looking over things,

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:32.160
looking at suggestions.

00:29:32.160 --> 00:29:40.160
So as a leader, you need to be able to do that, but you also need to be able to have some good constructive criticism

00:29:40.160 --> 00:29:46.160
on things they need to improve upon or things they need to work on or just learn about,

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:52.160
but also letting them know that that's common for anybody in this industry.

00:29:52.160 --> 00:29:57.160
Again, the guy that I was talking to this morning, he goes, I'm embarrassed by my code, and I said, no, don't be embarrassed.

00:29:57.160 --> 00:29:58.160
This is how we learn.

00:29:58.160 --> 00:30:04.160
This is how we go, and I think it was Hadley that I heard from Hadley, but it was 10 years ago.

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:10.160
You go through a million lines of code just to get one good – a million lines of bad code to get to one line of good code

00:30:10.160 --> 00:30:12.160
or something like that.

00:30:12.160 --> 00:30:19.160
So it takes a lot of practice to go through your code to get to that level that your code is easier to read

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:21.160
or easier to work with and things like that.

00:30:21.160 --> 00:30:23.160
So never be embarrassed with your code.

00:30:23.160 --> 00:30:27.160
Just get it out there and work with it.

00:30:27.160 --> 00:30:28.160
Those are great tips.

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:30.160
