Sure. So when I think people analytics, one question that comes to mind is understanding how interview questions and the interview process would potentially translate to later job performance.

00:38:19.159 --> 00:38:25.159
I'm just curious if that's something that has been looked into at NASA and like whether technical interviews,

00:38:25.159 --> 00:38:32.159
take home projects or specific questions truly lead to a better performance from a new employee.

00:38:32.159 --> 00:38:40.159
And if not NASA, if the rest of the group has any input, I'd be curious to know if really anyone's working on that.

00:38:40.159 --> 00:38:54.159
So. To a degree, I mean, we started a project to take a look at it was more focused around helping our raters identify executive level individuals.

00:38:54.159 --> 00:39:02.159
So within the government, you've got your general services group, which, you know, your GS 15 down and on down.

00:39:02.159 --> 00:39:06.159
Then you have your executive level group, which are those that are appointed.

00:39:06.159 --> 00:39:12.159
You know, they apply for them, but they still have to be appointed by the administration to that position.

00:39:12.159 --> 00:39:17.159
In order to get to that to to apply for that, you have to answer a huge level.

00:39:17.159 --> 00:39:27.159
Well, not a huge. There's. Total of eight questions, I think, and two technical qualification, technical specific and technical general questions.

00:39:27.159 --> 00:39:36.159
And raters look at those responses and say, OK, this person fully qualified or fully answer that question, or this person just missed the mark on that question.

00:39:36.159 --> 00:39:42.159
And some of them are more technical. Some of them are also around how you lead and some of your examples there.

00:39:42.159 --> 00:40:00.159
So we've had an initiative underway to take a look at past responses to see, can we determine, was this a good response or a not so good response or just a terrible response based on how raters have rated them in the past?

00:40:01.159 --> 00:40:14.159
It's tricky because now we're taught where it's very subjective in the sense we're trying to evaluate how somebody wrote what they wrote and what they write, actually answer that.

00:40:14.159 --> 00:40:24.159
Not only to answer the question, but provide good substance to that to that question and did it did it in a way that that made sense and provided value.

00:40:25.159 --> 00:40:32.159
In other words, like me, I'm not rambling, not a whole lot of rambling, but was very concise and very accurate in what they were trying to do.

00:40:32.159 --> 00:40:41.159
It's. It was difficult because we came across a lot of issues with the raters, first of all, that the raters didn't all rate the same.

00:40:41.159 --> 00:40:47.159
They weren't trained how to rate or what to look for. It was just their subjective based on their experience.

00:40:47.159 --> 00:40:54.159
So it's hard to identify how somebody may have rated somebody really good, but another rater rated them not so good or just average.

00:40:54.159 --> 00:41:01.159
So there was a lot of discrepancies there. And then you have to think about the ethical and legal ramifications on that.

00:41:02.159 --> 00:41:14.159
Can we justify the algorithm's response legally to the results that came out? And those are things that we had. So there's a lot of nuances, a lot of things you have to consider.

00:41:14.159 --> 00:41:19.159
But it's something we are looking at and trying to figure out if there's a way of doing it.

00:41:20.159 --> 00:41:35.159
And actually, I think I saw a Kaggle content or event just recently about evaluating essays, but primarily they were looking at sixth to 12th grade essays.

00:41:35.159 --> 00:41:45.159
But the concept is very similar to that, evaluating how they wrote it and the value of not just the quality of the writing, but the content that was in there.

00:41:45.159 --> 00:41:48.159
Was it a good content?

00:41:51.159 --> 00:41:59.159
Thanks, David. I realize there are a lot of other anonymous questions that came in, too, so I want to get to some of those.

00:41:59.159 --> 00:42:07.159
One was, do you have opinions on open source? Was it scary for people at NASA to introduce it?

00:42:08.159 --> 00:42:21.159
Yes, I have opinions on open source. I am a big open source fan. I tend to believe it's – for more often than not, it's probably a lot better.

00:42:21.159 --> 00:42:33.159
Well, it's easier to understand, easier to work with. And of course, as a software developer myself, it's good to know – being able to see the pack in a lot of times, which you can't see on some of the Kot type products.

00:42:34.159 --> 00:42:45.159
Was it scary? I think in some cases, for some groups, it was scary. For IT security, it was scary because it's open source and you've got to really take a look at it, don't know what's inside of it.

00:42:45.159 --> 00:42:54.159
It hasn't been vetted. It hasn't gone through a lot of different security clearances or checks or things like that.

00:42:55.159 --> 00:43:05.159
So it was scary for them until it became more ubiquitous across the industries being utilized. This was many years ago when open source was just coming out.

00:43:05.159 --> 00:43:11.159
The other scary part is maintenance and operations of the open source software.

00:43:12.159 --> 00:43:17.159
You have many open source companies, of course, have their commercial sites where you can use them for operation.

00:43:17.159 --> 00:43:27.159
But a lot of organizations use open source because it's less costly to buy the software, but there's still a cost to maintain it and operate it and manage it.

00:43:27.159 --> 00:43:40.159
And people didn't understand that, and people then were realizing this because in some cases, it was costing them more to use the open source software than a commercial product because they didn't have the staff to manage that open source software.

00:43:41.159 --> 00:43:50.159
And maintain it. And unfortunately, kind of like I'm doing with RStudio right now, even though it's a commercial product, I started it as an open source.

00:43:50.159 --> 00:43:55.159
I learned how to manage it and maintain it, but we don't have a whole lot of other people that know how to manage it and maintain it.

00:43:55.159 --> 00:43:58.159
So we've got to train those folks up, which is an additional cost.

00:44:00.159 --> 00:44:09.159
But as we get more to the point that we're using it as a more enterprise type capability, that cost will go down because more and more people are utilizing and going there.

00:44:09.159 --> 00:44:11.159
Did I answer the entire question?

00:44:15.159 --> 00:44:18.159
I don't know who asked it, but I think that answered it.

00:44:18.159 --> 00:44:24.159
If anybody wants more context or follow-up, feel free to use the chat, too.

00:44:24.159 --> 00:44:26.159
Thank you, David.

00:44:26.159 --> 00:44:30.159
Jose, I think I saw your hand was raised at some point.

00:44:30.159 --> 00:44:31.159
Yes.

00:44:31.159 --> 00:44:32.159
Okay.

00:44:32.159 --> 00:44:38.159
I just was a little curious about the data retention policies at NASA.

00:44:38.159 --> 00:44:42.159
And I also wanted to ask, do you have to get the poly to work there?

00:44:42.159 --> 00:44:47.159
Or how does it work when you're selected as a candidate?

00:44:49.159 --> 00:44:50.159
Okay.

00:44:50.159 --> 00:44:51.159
Data retention.

00:44:51.159 --> 00:44:54.159
Well, there's data retention and there's records retention.

00:44:54.159 --> 00:44:56.159
A couple of different things.

00:44:56.159 --> 00:45:02.159
There is a government standard for records retention on how long we have to keep a record.

00:45:02.159 --> 00:45:05.159
Now, a record could be different than a data site.

00:45:05.159 --> 00:45:17.159
So data retention, on the other side, that's more dependent on the data owners and their organization and how long they want to retain that data and what it's being used for.

00:45:17.159 --> 00:45:21.159
So there's different data governance policies depending on the organization.

00:45:22.159 --> 00:45:26.159
By organizations at NASA, I'm talking about we're broken down, of course, into centers.

00:45:26.159 --> 00:45:36.159
And then across the centers, you have different organizations inside the centers from their HR, their procurement, to their engineering department, to their medical department, things like that.

00:45:36.159 --> 00:45:43.159
Then across NASA, you also have programs, SSMD, the Space Mission Directorate, and ARMD.

00:45:43.159 --> 00:45:47.159
So there's a lot of different ways NASA is broken down.

00:45:47.159 --> 00:45:50.159
So each of them may have their own data governance and data retention policy.

00:45:50.159 --> 00:46:00.159
So to get a job within NASA as a civil servant, one of the first criteria is you have to be a U.S. citizen.

00:46:00.159 --> 00:46:16.159
Then once you get through the process, if your resume makes it through that, they do use some kind of certification algorithm to say, okay, did this resume meet what was asked for in the job announcement?

00:46:16.159 --> 00:46:20.159
Did you capture all of the different concepts that we were looking for?

00:46:20.159 --> 00:46:22.159
So we've got a list of requirements there.

00:46:22.159 --> 00:46:27.159
Did your resume show that you have that requirement?

00:46:27.159 --> 00:46:29.159
And if so, then you get what's called certified.

00:46:29.159 --> 00:46:31.159
That means your resume cleared that.

00:46:31.159 --> 00:46:36.159
Then it goes to the hiring official to decide, okay, now I've got all these resumes.

00:46:36.159 --> 00:46:39.159
I've got to read all these resumes to see which ones I want to pull out.

00:46:40.159 --> 00:46:52.159
And we are looking at ways of using some type of methodologies or algorithms to kind of fine-tune that a little bit and then pull out ones that the hiring official may think are better for their current announcement.

00:46:52.159 --> 00:46:54.159
And that's something we're still working on.

00:46:54.159 --> 00:46:56.159
Then you go through the interview process.

00:46:56.159 --> 00:47:02.159
And the interview process, depending, again, on the organization, it could be a series of questions.

00:47:02.159 --> 00:47:04.159
And it's usually a panel interview.

00:47:04.159 --> 00:47:08.159
You may have anywhere from three to four people on the panel that ask you questions.

00:47:08.159 --> 00:47:11.159
And then afterwards, they get together and rate those questions.

00:47:11.159 --> 00:47:19.159
And then depending on, they either bring you back for second interviews and then spoil it down until they finally make a selection.

00:47:19.159 --> 00:47:23.159
But a polygraph, I think that's what the question was.

00:47:23.159 --> 00:47:24.159
Yes.

00:47:24.159 --> 00:47:27.159
A polygraph is not – I have not seen a polygraph.

00:47:27.159 --> 00:47:29.159
But you do get a background check.

00:47:29.159 --> 00:47:33.159
And those background checks are lengthy, can be lengthy.

00:47:33.159 --> 00:47:44.159
I've got two new hires that there are a few things that I can't give them access to because their security level, their clearance level hasn't reached the level that I need them to because their background check hasn't completed yet.

00:47:44.159 --> 00:47:45.159
One more thing.

00:47:45.159 --> 00:47:57.159
When there's pictures taken, say, by the rovers out there in Mars and stuff like that, do you get to capture the geolocation on each picture and use that in your data sets?

00:47:57.159 --> 00:48:04.159
Or is that depending on the technology that was available at that time?

00:48:04.159 --> 00:48:12.159
Or do you get to see any of this information or process it in real time?

00:48:12.159 --> 00:48:14.159
Good question.

00:48:14.159 --> 00:48:19.159
Not my area of expertise as far as the data set itself.

00:48:19.159 --> 00:48:22.159
I mean, I can get access to the images that come out.

00:48:22.159 --> 00:48:25.159
And everybody should have access through NASA images.

00:48:25.159 --> 00:48:28.159
I think it's one of the links there.

00:48:28.159 --> 00:48:32.159
But I'm going to say yes, at least on the latest.

00:48:32.159 --> 00:48:38.159
We have some kind of – let me think through that.

00:48:38.159 --> 00:48:41.159
Yeah, I'm sure they've got some way of mapping it out and locations on there.

00:48:41.159 --> 00:48:43.159
And they should have that capability available there.

00:48:43.159 --> 00:48:46.159
And the metadata should be stored in the metadata somewhere.

00:48:46.159 --> 00:48:49.159
Thank you.

00:48:49.159 --> 00:48:57.159
David, I see someone had asked earlier, how does NASA tackle an aging workforce?

00:48:57.159 --> 00:49:03.159
A lot of fundamental knowledge may be lost if a new cohort can't be trained before existing staff retire.

00:49:03.159 --> 00:49:07.159
Another excellent question, because we do.

00:49:08.159 --> 00:49:12.159
Man, I was just playing around with some data earlier and looking at the average age of our individuals.

00:49:12.159 --> 00:49:15.159
And we're up there in the 50-60 area.

00:49:15.159 --> 00:49:22.159
If you look at the distribution, we've got a lot of – most of our folks are in the 50-60 age group

00:49:22.159 --> 00:49:24.159
and pretty close to retirement.

00:49:24.159 --> 00:49:33.159
So one of the things we did in 2009, if I remember correctly, NASA implemented a –

00:49:33.159 --> 00:49:37.159
they already had knowledge management offices across each of the centers.

00:49:37.159 --> 00:49:41.159
But they implemented a chief knowledge officer across the agency.

00:49:41.159 --> 00:49:50.159
And one of the primary objectives of that office there was to help capture information across the agency.

00:49:50.159 --> 00:49:53.159
So each of the centers do things maybe a little differently.

00:49:53.159 --> 00:49:57.159
While I was at JSC, anybody that was getting to retire that was –

00:49:57.159 --> 00:50:01.159
what they would consider a high-level target as far as knowledge,

00:50:01.159 --> 00:50:07.159
they would interview them and basically write a book on everything that they knew and try to capture that.

00:50:07.159 --> 00:50:13.159
There's also other management techniques that we – knowledge management techniques we use, lessons learned,

00:50:13.159 --> 00:50:17.159
trying to capture that across the various organizations, case studies,

00:50:17.159 --> 00:50:21.159
looking at different issues or things that may have happened and developing case studies on that.

00:50:21.159 --> 00:50:25.159
We've also started to implement – many different groups do it.

00:50:25.159 --> 00:50:30.159
Again, sometimes we can be kind of a wild, wild west where each organization is doing some of their own things.

00:50:30.159 --> 00:50:36.159
But a couple of groups have instituted some very good wikis to where people are capturing this data.

00:50:36.159 --> 00:50:41.159
Just for that example, they've realized that we have an aging workforce and we need to capture this information.

00:50:41.159 --> 00:50:43.159
So those things are going to there.

00:50:43.159 --> 00:50:49.159
So there's a lot of things going on to try to capture from a knowledge management perspective this type of data

00:50:49.159 --> 00:50:59.159
and making it available and searchable for people that are coming in now and in the future.

00:50:59.159 --> 00:51:01.159
Thanks, David.

00:51:01.159 --> 00:51:06.159
Okay, I know an hour is going by very quickly and there are a lot of questions still here,

00:51:06.159 --> 00:51:10.159
so I'm going to try and go through a few more.

00:51:10.159 --> 00:51:15.159
One was, how do you all think about system assessment?

00:51:15.159 --> 00:51:22.159
Any follow-up comparing a hire's actual performance to the prediction?

00:51:22.159 --> 00:51:25.159
And then also, how do you think about equity and diversity?

00:51:25.159 --> 00:51:28.159
That's a lot of questions, maybe, into one.

00:51:28.159 --> 00:51:35.159
So we're not yet into the complete predictive capabilities within people analytics.

00:51:35.159 --> 00:51:42.159
One of the things I had to do early on to management is to first get them to understand the difference

00:51:42.159 --> 00:51:48.159
between descriptive and predictive and try and understand why we needed to upscale

00:51:48.159 --> 00:51:52.159
or improve our infrastructure, especially with the amount of data.

00:51:52.159 --> 00:51:54.159
They were somewhat happy with it.

00:51:54.159 --> 00:51:56.159
Well, we've got all this data here and we're able to use it.

00:51:56.159 --> 00:51:58.159
Well, kind of you're able to use it.

00:51:58.159 --> 00:52:04.159
I'm able to tell you right now what's good today based on this data set,

00:52:04.159 --> 00:52:08.159
but I can't look in the past and I can't use that data to tell you what we might be able to see

00:52:08.159 --> 00:52:14.159
in the future, and that's where we need to get to more of a predictive model.

00:52:14.159 --> 00:52:18.159
So I guess the answer to the first question is, no, we can't do that right now,

00:52:18.159 --> 00:52:22.159
but it's definitely something that is on my roadmap to try to be able to look at those types

00:52:22.159 --> 00:52:28.159
of things to understand, you know, did we hire, did the people we hire actually pan out, I guess,

00:52:28.159 --> 00:52:34.159
for lack of a better phrase, and how do you define diversity, equity, inclusion?

00:52:34.159 --> 00:52:37.159
So there's a lot of things out there.

00:52:37.159 --> 00:52:39.159
This book, I can't get to it.

00:52:39.159 --> 00:52:40.159
I don't know if you can see.

00:52:40.159 --> 00:52:46.159
This is a decent book for DEIA Inclusalytics, the new terminology they put out there.

00:52:47.159 --> 00:52:52.159
It's a good book just to understand DEIA or diversity, equity, inclusion, and accessibility,

00:52:52.159 --> 00:52:55.159
different concepts around it.

00:52:55.159 --> 00:53:03.159
This book just came out a couple of months ago, but it's all depends on, well,

00:53:03.159 --> 00:53:06.159
diversity is fairly easy enough, I think, to understand, you know,

00:53:06.159 --> 00:53:10.159
is your population that you're working with diverse enough?

00:53:10.159 --> 00:53:14.159
The key there is diverse compared to what?

00:53:14.159 --> 00:53:20.159
You know, is it just supposed to be 50-50 all the way across, or what are we looking at?

00:53:20.159 --> 00:53:25.159
So do we compare it against the population across the United States, across the whole world,

00:53:25.159 --> 00:53:28.159
across the area, you know, that we're looking at?

00:53:28.159 --> 00:53:30.159
You know, if I'm at Johnson Space Center in Houston,

00:53:30.159 --> 00:53:34.159
am I only concerned about the population around that area?

00:53:34.159 --> 00:53:38.159
Or, you know, so that's a lot of questions that have to be answered around there.

00:53:39.159 --> 00:53:44.159
And inclusion, more about whether the individual feels like they belong

00:53:44.159 --> 00:53:50.159
and they're being heard within that organization.

00:53:50.159 --> 00:53:51.159
